Important Insight

Before the single element:

nums[even] == nums[even + 1]

After the single element:

nums[even] != nums[even + 1]

This observation allows Binary Search.

Binary Search Idea

Choose a middle index.

Make sure mid is even.

if(mid % 2 == 1){
    mid--;
}
Why?

We always want to compare:

Pair Start  → Pair End

Example:

Index: 4 5
Value: 3 3

So mid should point to the first element of a pair.

Cases
Case 1
nums[mid] == nums[mid + 1]

Pair is valid.

This means:

Single element lies on the right side.

Move:

low = mid + 2;
Case 2
nums[mid] != nums[mid + 1]

Pair is broken.

This means:

Single element lies on the left side
or
mid itself is the answer.

Move:

high = mid;
Code
class Solution {

    public int singleNonDuplicate(int[] nums) {

        int low = 0;
        int high = nums.length - 1;

        while(low < high) {

            int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

            // Make mid even
            if(mid % 2 == 1) {
                mid--;
            }

            if(nums[mid] == nums[mid + 1]) {
                low = mid + 2;
            }
            else {
                high = mid;
            }
        }

        return nums[low];
    }
}
